        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>Is my ideal weight exactly the same as my BMI?</h3>
            <p>No. Standard BMI charts offer a very wide "range" of structurally healthy weights (sometimes a 30-40 pound window). Ideal weight formulas attempt to mathematically pin down the absolute most perfect, singular target weight precisely in the center of that safety bracket.</p>
            
            <h3>What if I am structurally very muscular?</h3>
            <p>As with all generalized medical formulas, the Devine calculation operates blindly on statistical averages. Highly muscular athletes with massive bone density will likely find their "ideal weight" incredibly low and difficult to reach safely. Consider tracking body fat percentages instead.</p>
            
            <h3>Does my age change my ideal weight target?</h3>
            <p>Strictly mathematically via the formula? No. Medically? Yes. Many doctors advise maintaining a slightly higher BMI as individuals cross into their late 60s and 70s to combat osteoporosis and natural frailty risks.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Mastering exactly how to calculate ideal weight frames a definitive numerical bullseye for your diet. By leaning on established medical models like the Devine formula, intelligently interpreting the rigidity of the math regarding age and heavy musculature, and deploying robust automated calculators mapped alongside BMI references, you can dictate a fitness timeline built completely around safety rather than aesthetics.</p>
